        "sequence.stats([array], [field_or_function]) \8594 object\nsequence.stats([array]) \8594 object\n\nIf a command like 'stats' existed, the map-reduce query in the example below could be written more elegantly.\n\nExample:\n\nEXPECTED RESULT:\n\n```\n[\n{\n\"group\":  \"value-1\" ,\n\"reduction\": {\n\"count\": 2 ,\n\"sum\": 9 ,\n\"min\": 4 ,\n\"max\": 5\n}\n} , [...]\n```\n\nORIGINAL QUERY:\n\n```\nr.table('mytable').group('group-attr')\n.map(r.row('num-attr')).map(function(x){return{\n  'count': 1,\n  'sum': x,\n  'min': x,\n  'max': x\n  }})\n  .reduce(function(a, b){return{\n    'count': a('count').add(b('count')),\n    'sum': a('sum').add(b('sum')),\n    'min': r.branch(a('min').lt(b('min')), a('min'), b('min')),\n    'max': r.branch(a('max').gt(b('max')), a('max'), b('max'))\n    }})\n```\n\nstats query:\n\n```\nr.table('mytable').group('group-attr')\n.stats([r.count(), r.sum(), r.min(), r.max()], 'num-attr')\n\nor\n\nr.table('mytable').group('group-attr')\n.stats([r.count(), r.sum('num-attr'), r.min('num-attr'), r.max('num-attr')])\n\nor (not equivalent, but it shows other possibilities)\n\nr.table('mytable').group('group-attr')\n.stats([r.count(), r.sum('num-attr-1'), r.min('num-attr-2'), r.max('num-attr-3'), r.avg('num-attr-4')])\n```\n"
